WEBVTT

00:01.180 --> 00:02.240
This is Daryl Lane.

00:02.520 --> 00:03.340
And this is Bill Vernon.

00:03.700 --> 00:06.560
And we'll be talking with some prominent authors about the New Wave in science fiction.

00:06.920 --> 00:11.400
The New Wave, which began in the mid-1960s, was simply a New Wave writing science fiction.

00:12.040 --> 00:13.880
Yes, and that newness was seen in many areas.

00:14.420 --> 00:16.940
There was often something unusual, for instance, about the style.

00:17.400 --> 00:19.480
Character and psychology were given much more emphasis.

00:20.180 --> 00:24.620
And also the New Wave treated themes such as sex and religion that science fiction hadn't really touched before.

00:25.020 --> 00:25.280
Right.

00:25.280 --> 00:30.020
And the authors who wrote about these themes were interested in changing the traditional science fiction formulas

00:30.020 --> 00:34.000
which had been around since the pulp era of the 1920s, 30s, and 40s.

00:34.360 --> 00:35.480
You know that type of story.

00:35.880 --> 00:41.200
It's one in which science is glorified and the hero rescues earth from hordes of menacing, bug-eyed monsters.

00:42.920 --> 00:46.900
Frederick Paul, who's been an author, an editor, and an agent in the field of science fiction,

00:47.280 --> 00:48.960
has a few things to say about that change.

00:49.840 --> 00:59.100
New Wave was an attempt, I guess, 15 years ago or more of a number of writers to break away from the traditional kinds of science fiction.

00:59.420 --> 01:01.760
In fact, most of them didn't want to call it science fiction anymore.

01:02.080 --> 01:05.560
They didn't want to call it speculative fiction or call it nothing at all.

01:06.200 --> 01:12.300
And they were interested primarily in writing about interspaces rather than outer space,

01:12.580 --> 01:18.060
and secondarily, a lot of them in things like the drug culture and rock music and so on.

01:18.060 --> 01:25.420
But in the rather bitter internal struggle that went on in science fiction,

01:25.680 --> 01:27.840
a lot of people take sides one way or the other.

01:28.560 --> 01:30.180
I think everyone was deeply affected.

01:30.880 --> 01:36.360
We'll need to remember here that New Wave wasn't really a planned and deliberate movement by a unified group of writers.

01:37.040 --> 01:40.360
One of the principal proponents of the New Wave, author Norman Spinrad,

01:40.840 --> 01:43.440
believes it was just a bunch of diverse writers doing their own thing.

01:43.440 --> 01:49.080
It was an old way, but there was never as a coherent philosophy in school of science fiction,

01:49.120 --> 01:51.700
but there was never a New Wave in the same sense.

01:52.080 --> 01:53.020
There were a lot of ways.

01:53.180 --> 01:55.120
There were a lot of different people doing a lot of different things.

01:56.060 --> 01:58.620
The people that were identified as New Wave were very diverse.

01:59.280 --> 02:06.300
What I was actually writing is very different to what Tom Dish was writing, or Boulard, or Zalazny and Delaney,

02:06.400 --> 02:08.000
were also identified as New Wave writers.

02:08.000 --> 02:15.880
This stuff is much more, you know, Zalazny and Delaney and myself and Boulard and all this and Mike.

02:16.980 --> 02:25.140
We were all, there were more differences between our work than between our work taking us to the talkality and the old stuff.

02:25.640 --> 02:30.100
There was more difference within the so-called New Wave than there was within the so-called old wave.

02:30.660 --> 02:34.660
But Spinrad also thinks the New Wave was tightly connected to what was happening in society.

02:34.660 --> 02:37.820
And of course this mirrored the cultural appointment at the time.

02:37.980 --> 02:43.540
It mirrored what was happening politically, it mirrored what was happening in music, it mirrored what was happening in movies.

02:43.880 --> 02:47.960
It was a phenomenon that went through the western civilizations, a whole.

02:48.780 --> 02:51.300
Some authors maintain that the New Wave is now dead.

02:51.860 --> 02:57.420
Five-time Hugo winner Larry Niven, the author of Ring World, thinks there's a good reason for its demise.

02:57.420 --> 03:05.760
The New Wave is a very persuasive thing and very easy to use to justify bad stories.

03:07.160 --> 03:08.400
I think that's what killed it.

03:08.880 --> 03:20.680
Not that increased characterization and experiments with typography and story format are a bad thing in themselves,

03:20.860 --> 03:24.620
but it's so easy to use New Wave to justify a bad story.

03:24.620 --> 03:27.020
It was bound to collapse.

03:33.400 --> 03:39.720
That may be so, but lots of others feel that the influence of the New Wave is still around, though its presence isn't as intense as before.

03:40.460 --> 03:42.780
It's left its mark on the field, no doubt about that.

03:43.480 --> 03:46.720
Science fiction has been broadened, maybe enhanced somehow because of it.

03:47.200 --> 03:48.480
Frederick Paul states it well.

03:49.100 --> 03:56.480
And the New Wave, if nothing else, taught a bunch of old dinosaurs like Asimov and Heinlein and Meeth,

03:57.280 --> 04:00.520
that there were nontraditional ways of constructing a novel.

04:00.980 --> 04:04.720
See, most of us had grown up when science fiction was in the pulp magazines,

04:04.840 --> 04:08.580
and most of it was written according to some variant of the pulp formula.

04:09.260 --> 04:10.780
It turned out that wasn't necessary.

04:11.360 --> 04:15.020
And I think the New Wave is responsible for teaching us that.

