05:30.200 --> 05:32.540
Of all the themes handled by science fiction authors,

05:32.920 --> 05:36.360
that of alien contact has been one of the most consistently popular and fascinating.

05:37.080 --> 05:38.100
For a good reason, too.

05:38.920 --> 05:41.840
Aliens have always been one of the biggest attractions of science fiction.

05:42.440 --> 05:45.220
Whether they be the hostile bug-eyed monsters of the old pulp magazines

05:45.220 --> 05:47.660
or the friendly creatures of close encounters of the third kind.

05:47.660 --> 05:52.340
And they become even more fascinating when you find them in what some people call a first contact story.

05:52.880 --> 05:57.560
First contact, as the term implies, describes the very first meeting between humans and an alien species.

05:58.160 --> 06:01.840
In the past, stories of alien contact were usually written as thrillers,

06:02.120 --> 06:04.780
with the sole and simple intention of scaring readers.

06:05.320 --> 06:09.360
H.G. Wells' The War of the Worlds is probably the best example of that type of story.

06:09.860 --> 06:10.820
But that's changed.

06:11.480 --> 06:14.560
Many contemporary writers have provided more thoughtful treatments of aliens,

06:14.560 --> 06:18.240
deepening the realism and the significance of narratives of alien contact.

06:18.740 --> 06:22.240
Of course, before you can have a story of alien contact, you must first have some aliens.

06:23.080 --> 06:25.980
One of the most provocative descriptions of aliens in all of science fiction

06:25.980 --> 06:28.900
is found in Larry Niven's and Jerry Pranell's The Mote in God's Eye,

06:29.320 --> 06:32.060
considered by many to be the finest of all first contact stories.

06:32.580 --> 06:37.220
The success of this book is largely due to the unique and ingenious aliens, the Motees,

06:37.480 --> 06:39.000
the Niven created for the story.

06:39.520 --> 06:43.520
It's interesting, though, that Niven says he doesn't really create aliens for a story,

06:43.520 --> 06:45.660
but suggests that it's the other way around.

06:46.240 --> 06:50.160
But I always design aliens for themselves.

06:50.540 --> 06:54.480
I almost never design an alien to match a story.

06:55.140 --> 06:59.720
The story, some story, will eventually include the alien.

07:00.220 --> 07:01.700
The alien stands for itself.

07:02.540 --> 07:06.320
There are two particularly fascinating things that Niven incorporated into these Motees.

07:06.780 --> 07:08.300
One is the fact that they are not symmetrical.

07:08.760 --> 07:11.760
They have a head, torso, legs, and arms, as humans do,

07:11.760 --> 07:13.600
but the arms are disproportionate.

07:13.980 --> 07:16.240
One is small and thin, and the other is large and powerful.

07:16.760 --> 07:21.140
Right. Niven says he took that idea from studying the structures of living creatures on Earth.

07:21.760 --> 07:30.260
In that case, I had the idea that I was following a progression with a protozoan with an amoeba.

07:30.780 --> 07:33.800
You get radial symmetry inside and out.

07:35.020 --> 07:40.980
You move up a goodly distance, and you find starfishes with radial symmetry on the outside

07:40.980 --> 07:43.080
and bilateral symmetry on the inside.

07:43.340 --> 07:48.400
You move up a little further, and you find flat worms and worms of all stents.

07:49.420 --> 07:53.180
At the level of bilateral symmetry inside and out.

07:53.820 --> 07:58.120
Go as far as a human, and you find bilateral symmetry on the outside,

07:58.120 --> 08:03.500
and no symmetry, well, half symmetrical on the inside.

08:03.920 --> 08:07.000
The lungs look symmetrical, the kidneys look symmetrical,

08:07.560 --> 08:10.780
the intestines look like somebody dropped a plate of spaghetti.

08:11.340 --> 08:13.860
I tried to move on to the next step,

08:16.900 --> 08:19.460
bilaterally unsymmetrical on the outside,

08:20.040 --> 08:23.960
and I got the original Motee, which was the engineer's one.

08:23.960 --> 08:28.360
The other ingenious idea Niven developed for the Motees is the way they construct and use machines.

08:29.020 --> 08:34.120
They're highly skilled tool users, but they have no standard pre-manufactured machines, parts, or tools.

08:34.740 --> 08:38.560
They simply alter or reshape whatever they find around them at the time to suit their needs.

08:39.200 --> 08:41.680
And Niven says that particular idea just came to him.

08:42.180 --> 08:43.600
It seemed interesting and even logical.

08:44.440 --> 08:49.640
I was just playing with the ideas at that point, and that one seemed like a fun one.

08:49.640 --> 08:57.020
It also seemed likely enough, if you've got a critter with not much intelligence

08:57.020 --> 09:02.880
except in the direction of toolmaking and tool altering, then why not?

09:03.780 --> 09:08.720
The thing has to keep testing its ability, or it will lose it.

09:09.320 --> 09:13.980
It might as well be designing something every time it needs a specific machine.

09:14.480 --> 09:18.000
Besides the ingenuity Niven demonstrated in creating the Motees,

09:18.000 --> 09:21.900
he and Purnell also used some unexpected twists into the first contact theme.

09:22.640 --> 09:27.480
A reader interested in alien contact cannot afford to overlook the Motee in God's eye.

