11:06.760 --> 11:10.860
This is David Cruz. Today we begin an interview with author Larry Niven.

11:15.080 --> 11:19.080
Even a casual reader of science fiction, if asked to name his favorite authors,

11:19.540 --> 11:21.680
would almost certainly mention the name of Larry Niven.

11:22.480 --> 11:25.860
Niven's popularity rests on a solid and extensive body of work,

11:25.980 --> 11:29.200
but one particular novel seems to have captivated science fiction fans.

11:29.800 --> 11:35.340
That casual reader who named Niven as one of his favorite authors would likely pick Ringworld as Niven's finest work.

11:36.140 --> 11:39.800
The Ringworld is an immense ring, large enough to hold three million Earths.

11:39.800 --> 11:43.800
It has a thousand mile high wall on each side to hold in its atmosphere.

11:44.360 --> 11:45.540
It has continents and oceans.

11:46.160 --> 11:49.100
The Ringworld contains trillions of inhabitants of different species

11:49.100 --> 11:51.660
and derives energy from the sun at its center.

11:52.560 --> 11:55.920
Niven recalls where he obtained the idea for such a fantastic structure.

12:09.800 --> 12:12.840
Suddenly I ran across an article about Dyson Spears.

12:13.100 --> 12:19.960
A picture of that is a golf ball 93 million miles in radius with a sun at the center.

12:20.800 --> 12:25.580
And gravity generators all around the outside so he would live on the inside,

12:25.840 --> 12:30.480
terraforming it with oceans and soil and air.

12:31.760 --> 12:35.740
I ran across that and I didn't like it. I thought it could be improved.

12:36.620 --> 12:38.100
And I wound up with the Ringworld.

12:38.960 --> 12:41.020
Readers were fascinated with the Ringworld.

12:41.340 --> 12:44.320
So fascinated in fact that they studied the science behind it

12:44.320 --> 12:48.140
and wrote to Niven about what seemed to be errors or inconsistencies in the theory

12:48.140 --> 12:49.900
and design of the immense artifact.

12:50.800 --> 12:55.700
Column errors and elaborations because some of them don't really fit the errors.

12:55.940 --> 12:59.220
It's just something that hadn't gotten into the original book.

13:00.000 --> 13:02.520
One of the errors was spotted by some MIT students.

13:02.940 --> 13:05.200
It had to do with the instability of the Ringworld.

13:05.200 --> 13:10.360
I suspect that the Ringworld was unstable and I suspect that you need attitude jets.

13:11.020 --> 13:15.180
I was sure that the Ringworld was spinning fast enough to permit

13:15.180 --> 13:18.120
Blizzard RAM jets to be used as attitude jets,

13:18.240 --> 13:20.200
which means you don't have a fuel problem at all.

13:20.500 --> 13:21.640
You're burning the solar wind.

13:23.800 --> 13:28.340
But rapidly some MIT people demonstrated that the Ringworld was unstable

13:28.340 --> 13:32.040
and they were chanting it in the hall at the next Worldcon.

13:32.040 --> 13:35.260
The Ringworld is unstable. The Ringworld is unstable.

13:37.320 --> 13:43.700
It still took about seven years for anyone to figure out the exact numbers for the instability

13:43.700 --> 13:45.260
and they are horrifying.

13:46.880 --> 13:52.900
A major solar flare would have the Ringworld grinding against its sun in five years.

13:53.760 --> 13:58.720
Well, I worked it into a plot. That was one elaboration or error.

13:59.740 --> 14:04.320
Even teenage readers analyzed his Ringworld with a critical scientific eye.

14:05.180 --> 14:08.360
A high school class in Florida got to work on the Ringworld.

14:09.020 --> 14:16.860
And their conclusion was that the Ringworld's worst problem is that all the top soil would wind up in the oceans in about 3,000 years.

14:17.540 --> 14:21.980
There are no earthquakes on the Ringworld. No mountain building forces.

14:23.160 --> 14:27.740
But in a sequel, Ringworld engineers Niven attempted to correct such deficiencies.

14:27.740 --> 14:31.720
He devised a way to answer the criticism of the Florida high schoolers.

14:33.540 --> 14:42.300
Okay, that's a tough one. I set up a spill pipe system that runs the top, that runs the sea bottom mark from the sea bottoms

14:42.300 --> 14:45.720
under the Ringworld and up over the edge of the Ringwall.

14:47.560 --> 14:57.000
That even allows you some mind accumulation of useful metals.

14:57.880 --> 15:01.220
Fan response of that sort caused Ringworld engineers to be written.

15:01.780 --> 15:05.320
And although Niven once said he wouldn't write any more in the known space series,

15:05.500 --> 15:09.180
the body of stories to which Ringworld belongs, he's not so sure any more.

15:10.060 --> 15:17.640
I've given up saying that the known space series is dating. There's just no point in it.

15:17.760 --> 15:22.160
I've written five books worth of known space stories since I said that.

