17:15.000 --> 17:19.020
This is David Cruz. Today we continue our interview with author Larry Niven.

17:23.900 --> 17:29.020
Author Larry Niven has produced a body of science fiction that has made him one of the best selling authors in the field.

17:29.660 --> 17:32.980
A fairly large portion of his work falls into the known space series,

17:33.400 --> 17:38.080
a group of stories and novels with a consistent chronology and overall evolving pattern to them.

17:38.080 --> 17:40.680
Such a series is called a Future History.

17:41.360 --> 17:46.200
Niven believes there are some peculiar attractions a Future History has for a science fiction author.

17:46.840 --> 17:53.160
There had been Future Histories around, Poole Anderson and Robert Heinlein.

17:54.960 --> 18:01.240
And I tell you, I guess we each evolved the idea somewhat independently.

18:01.240 --> 18:06.740
And the idea is that if you carved out a consistent, workable future,

18:07.480 --> 18:10.100
it seems a shame to waste it on one story.

18:11.280 --> 18:19.660
You put it in the background because you want the background of a story to seem bigger than it is.

18:19.880 --> 18:22.040
So there are things that are simply unexplained.

18:25.760 --> 18:30.680
And if you think of more to say on a given subject, why you go with it?

18:30.680 --> 18:35.040
And if you think of a story that fits into the background of a previous story

18:35.040 --> 18:39.780
and allows you to elaborate on that background, sometimes you fall in love with the background.

18:40.400 --> 18:42.960
And presently you've got a bunch of stories that link.

18:44.240 --> 18:47.320
Ringworld is probably the best known story in Niven's Future History,

18:47.520 --> 18:51.200
but he's also written some best selling books that fall outside his known space series.

18:51.720 --> 18:57.360
Two of these, The Moat in God's Eye and Lucifer's Hammer, were written in collaboration with Jerry Pornell.

18:58.400 --> 19:01.000
Collaboration for a creative writer presents some problems.

19:01.500 --> 19:02.960
How is the work divided up, for instance?

19:03.420 --> 19:05.240
Is it hard to decide who writes what?

19:05.900 --> 19:09.480
Hard sometimes, but it always resolves.

19:10.280 --> 19:16.940
The question is who is most qualified to write a given scene that we have both decided needs writing?

19:17.780 --> 19:20.740
Before we start, we have the novel all laid out.

19:21.600 --> 19:24.680
We know what's going on virtually everywhere.

19:24.680 --> 19:26.800
And if we don't, it feels like we do.

19:27.660 --> 19:31.160
And if we find out we don't, we elaborate as we get to that section.

19:32.460 --> 19:35.940
Okay, the next question is who is qualified to write a given scene?

19:36.140 --> 19:37.100
Sometimes it's obvious.

19:38.040 --> 19:40.260
If we're dealing with a madman, he's mine.

19:41.020 --> 19:44.340
If we're dealing with military operations, it's Jerry's.

19:44.780 --> 19:46.620
Aliens are generally mine.

19:47.680 --> 19:49.740
Politics is generally Jerry's.

19:51.100 --> 19:53.480
Knowledge of history generally Jerry's.

19:53.480 --> 19:57.980
And a real evil son of a bitch Jerry usually creates him.

19:58.280 --> 20:01.080
And I usually run with him afterwards.

20:02.160 --> 20:07.340
But Niven resists classification, either as an author of future histories or as a collaborator.

20:07.760 --> 20:11.060
He sometimes branches out into seldom entered areas of science fiction.

20:11.540 --> 20:15.060
One of these areas is humor, something few science fiction writers attempt.

20:15.720 --> 20:18.340
What does he think his most successful piece of humor is?

20:18.340 --> 20:27.180
I suppose I could name, oh, man of steel, woman of queen eggs, which has gotten me the most laughs.

20:27.400 --> 20:30.400
I suppose everybody seems to have read it.

20:30.540 --> 20:33.100
And those who haven't have heard about it are cocktail parties.

20:34.080 --> 20:39.460
Niven's ready eye for humor can also be appreciated as he reveals that he's detected one of his own alien creations

20:39.460 --> 20:43.100
from Ringworld, a disguised Pearson's puppeteer here on Earth.

20:43.760 --> 20:46.720
I have reason to suspect the fair puppeteers on Earth.

20:47.920 --> 20:49.480
Look at the characteristics.

20:50.080 --> 20:50.880
Forget the shape.

20:51.020 --> 20:55.500
They must be masters of biology to hide that peculiar three-legged two-headed shape.

20:56.160 --> 20:58.120
But consider their characteristics.

20:58.380 --> 20:59.220
They are cowards.

21:01.060 --> 21:03.260
That is, they want everything utterly safe.

21:04.000 --> 21:05.440
No corners on anything.

21:05.720 --> 21:08.460
Everything is soft surfaces around the puppeteer world.

21:09.340 --> 21:11.880
They don't even keep their world near a sun.

21:11.880 --> 21:16.680
Regarding it is a runaway fusion reactor, which of course it is.

21:18.300 --> 21:26.680
So, desperate regard for safety, they plus an urge to meddle in the lifestyles of other species.

21:27.720 --> 21:33.560
Driving urge to meddle with practically no restraints attached.

21:34.220 --> 21:35.420
What does that remind you of?

21:36.080 --> 21:39.640
It seems nearly certain to me that Ralph Nader is a Pearson's puppeteer.

